{
  "What does PCA stand for in data analysis?": "",
  "Parallel Component Analysis": "",
  "Principal Component Analysis": "",
  "Primary Classification Approach": "",
  "Projected Correlation Algorithm": "",
  "PCA stands for Principal Component Analysis, a technique that identifies the directions (principal components) of maximum variance in high-dimensional data.": "",
  "In PCA, the principal components are the eigenvectors of which matrix?": "",
  "The identity matrix": "",
  "The inverse of the data matrix": "",
  "The covariance matrix of the data": "",
  "The data matrix itself": "",
  "The principal components are the eigenvectors of the covariance matrix (or equivalently, the right singular vectors of the centered data matrix). The eigenvalues represent the variance along each component.": "",
  "If a 2D dataset has covariance matrix [[4, 0], [0, 1]], what is the first principal component direction?": "",
  "(1, 1)/sqrt(2)": "",
  "(1, 0)": "",
  "(0, 1)": "",
  "(1, -1)/sqrt(2)": "",
  "Since the covariance matrix is diagonal, its eigenvectors are the standard basis vectors. The largest eigenvalue is 4, corresponding to eigenvector (1, 0), which is the first principal component.": "",
  "What percentage of total variance is captured by a principal component with eigenvalue 6 if the total variance (sum of all eigenvalues) is 10?": "",
  "60%": "",
  "40%": "",
  "80%": "",
  "16%": "",
  "The proportion of variance explained by a component is its eigenvalue divided by the sum of all eigenvalues: 6/10 = 60%.": "",
  "Before applying PCA, what preprocessing step is typically performed on the data?": "",
  "Squaring all data values": "",
  "Removing all negative values": "",
  "Centering the data by subtracting the mean of each feature": "",
  "Sorting the data by magnitude": "",
  "Data is centered by subtracting the mean of each feature so that the covariance matrix correctly captures the variance structure. Without centering, PCA would be influenced by the mean.": "",
  "In PCA, if you keep only the top k principal components from an n-dimensional dataset (k < n), what is this process called?": "",
  "Dimensionality reduction": "",
  "Feature crossing": "",
  "Data normalization": "",
  "Feature augmentation": "",
  "Keeping only the top k principal components reduces the data from n dimensions to k dimensions, a process called dimensionality reduction. This retains the most important variance while discarding less informative dimensions.": "",
  "PCA can also be computed using the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) of the centered data matrix X = USV^T. The principal components are the columns of which matrix?": "",
  "V": "",
  "S": "",
  "X": "",
  "U": "",
  "In X = USV^T, the columns of V are the right singular vectors, which are the eigenvectors of X^T X (proportional to the covariance matrix). These are the principal component directions.": "",
  "The covariance matrix used in PCA is always symmetric. What does this guarantee about its eigenvalues?": "",
  "They are all negative": "",
  "They are all integers": "",
  "They are all complex": "",
  "They are all real and non-negative": "",
  "The covariance matrix is symmetric and positive semi-definite, so all its eigenvalues are real and non-negative. The eigenvalues represent variances, which cannot be negative.": "",
  "If a dataset has 100 features and PCA reveals that 95% of the variance is captured by the first 5 components, the data compression ratio is approximately:": "",
  "5:100 or 20:1": "",
  "95:5 or 19:1": "",
  "1:1 (no compression)": "",
  "100:5 or 100:1": "",
  "Reducing from 100 to 5 dimensions gives a compression ratio of 100:5 = 20:1 while retaining 95% of the variance. This dramatic reduction is possible when data has strong correlations.": "",
  "In image compression using PCA, each image is typically represented as a vector. For a 64x64 grayscale image, what is the dimension of this vector?": "",
  "8192": "",
  "4096": "",
  "64": "",
  "128": "",
  "A 64x64 image has 64 * 64 = 4096 pixels. Each pixel value becomes one component of the vector, so the image is represented as a 4096-dimensional vector.": "",
  "What is a 'principal component' in PCA?": "",
  "A random direction chosen for projection": "",
  "An eigenvector of the covariance matrix representing a direction of maximum variance": "",
  "The most frequently occurring data point": "",
  "The mean of each feature in the dataset": "",
  "A principal component is an eigenvector of the data's covariance matrix, pointing in a direction that captures maximum variance. Principal components are ordered by decreasing eigenvalue (variance explained).": "",
  "What does 'explained variance ratio' mean in PCA?": "",
  "The ratio of original to compressed file size": "",
  "The percentage of data points retained after compression": "",
  "The ratio of the largest to smallest eigenvalue": "",
  "The fraction of total variance captured by a given principal component": "",
  "The explained variance ratio for the i-th component is lambda_i / sum(lambda_j), where lambda_i is its eigenvalue. It tells you what fraction of the total data variance that component captures.": "",
  "What is a 'scree plot' in PCA?": "",
  "A histogram of the data values": "",
  "A plot of data points in the first two principal component dimensions": "",
  "A scatter plot of the original features": "",
  "A bar chart showing the eigenvalues (or explained variance) for each component in decreasing order": "",
  "A scree plot displays eigenvalues (or explained variance ratios) in decreasing order. The 'elbow' in the plot helps determine how many principal components to retain for adequate variance explanation.": "",
  "What does 'lossy compression' mean in the context of PCA?": "",
  "The data loses its format during compression": "",
  "The compression algorithm sometimes fails": "",
  "The compressed data can be perfectly reconstructed": "",
  "Some information is permanently lost during compression, as the discarded components cannot be recovered": "",
  "PCA-based compression is lossy because discarding the lower-variance components permanently removes that information. The reconstruction approximates but does not exactly equal the original data.": "",
  "What is 'reconstruction error' in PCA?": "",
  "The rounding error in floating-point arithmetic": "",
  "The number of components that were discarded": "",
  "The difference between original data and its approximation from the retained principal components": "",
  "The error in computing eigenvalues": "",
  "Reconstruction error measures how well the reduced-dimension representation approximates the original data. It equals the sum of eigenvalues of the discarded components.": "",
  "What does 'loading' mean in PCA terminology?": "",
  "The time it takes to compute the principal components": "",
  "The number of data points used in the analysis": "",
  "The coefficients (entries) of the eigenvectors that describe how much each original variable contributes to a principal component": "",
  "The weight applied to each data point": "",
  "Loadings are the entries of the principal component eigenvectors. A large loading for a variable indicates that variable contributes strongly to that component's direction.": "",
  "What is an 'eigenface' in the context of PCA applied to face recognition?": "",
  "A face with perfectly symmetric features": "",
  "A principal component computed from a set of face images, representing a basic face pattern": "",
  "The average face in a dataset": "",
  "A face detection algorithm": "",
  "Eigenfaces are the principal components of a face image dataset. Each eigenface represents a fundamental face pattern, and any face can be approximately reconstructed as a weighted sum of eigenfaces.": "",
  "What does 'whitening' mean as a preprocessing step related to PCA?": "",
  "Transforming data so that all principal components have unit variance (covariance becomes the identity)": "",
  "Setting all negative values to zero": "",
  "Normalizing the data to have values between 0 and 1": "",
  "Removing all color information from images": "",
  "Whitening (or sphering) transforms data by projecting onto principal components and scaling each by 1/sqrt(eigenvalue), making the covariance matrix the identity. This decorrelates and equalizes variance.": "",
  "What is the 'score' of a data point in PCA?": "",
  "The distance from the data point to the mean": "",
  "The eigenvalue associated with the closest component": "",
  "A quality measure of how well PCA fits the data": "",
  "The coordinates of the data point in the principal component basis": "",
  "The PCA score of a data point is its projection onto the principal components, giving its coordinates in the new basis. These scores are the reduced-dimension representation of the original data.": "",
  "What does 'low-rank approximation' mean in the context of PCA and data compression?": "",
  "Rounding all data values to the nearest integer": "",
  "Using the smallest eigenvalues for the approximation": "",
  "Reducing the number of data points in the dataset": "",
  "Approximating a data matrix by a matrix of lower rank using only the top principal components": "",
  "A rank-k approximation of an m x n data matrix keeps only the top k singular values/components. By the Eckart-Young theorem, PCA provides the best rank-k approximation in the Frobenius norm sense.": "",
  "A genomics researcher has gene expression data with 20,000 genes across 200 patients. She applies PCA and finds that the first 3 components explain 80% of the variance. How much storage does the compressed representation require compared to the original?": "",
  "Only 3 values total": "",
  "200 * 200 = 40,000 values": "",
  "About 200 * 3 = 600 values plus 3 * 20000 = 60000 component vectors": "",
  "200 * 20000 = 4,000,000 values (no reduction)": "",
  "The compressed representation stores 200 * 3 = 600 scores plus 3 component vectors of length 20,000 (60,000 values) = 60,600 total, versus 4,000,000 in the original. This is roughly a 66:1 compression ratio.": "",
  "A computer vision engineer applies PCA to a set of 1000 face images, each 100x100 pixels. The covariance matrix she computes is of what size?": "",
  "1000 x 1000": "",
  "1000 x 10000": "",
  "100 x 100": "",
  "10000 x 10000": "",
  "Each 100x100 image is a 10,000-dimensional vector. The covariance matrix has dimensions equal to the number of features: 10,000 x 10,000. In practice, the smaller 1000x1000 matrix X X^T is often used instead.": "",
  "A music streaming service uses PCA to compress user preference vectors. If a user's original preference vector is x = (3, 1, 4, 1, 5) and the first principal component is e1 = (0, 0, 0, 0, 1), what is the user's score on the first component?": "",
  "5": "",
  "1": "",
  "3": "",
  "14": "",
  "The score is the projection x . e1 = 3(0) + 1(0) + 4(0) + 1(0) + 5(1) = 5. This means the user's preference is primarily captured by the 5th genre dimension in this principal direction.": "",
  "A financial analyst runs PCA on returns of 50 stocks and finds eigenvalues 25, 10, 5, 3, 2, 1, 1, ... (remaining near zero). How many components should she keep to capture at least 85% of the variance?": "",
  "2": "",
  "Total variance is approximately 25+10+5+3+2+1+1+... ~ 50 (assuming remaining sum to ~3). First 3 components: (25+10+5)/50 = 40/50 = 80%. Need to check: if total is closer to 47, then 40/47 = 85.1%. With 3 components capturing 40 out of ~47 total, she reaches approximately 85%.": "",
  "A satellite imaging company uses PCA for image compression. An image is stored as a 500x500 matrix. Using rank-10 PCA approximation, how many values need to be stored instead of 250,000?": "",
  "5,000": "",
  "500": "",
  "10,000": "",
  "250,000": "",
  "A rank-10 approximation of a 500x500 matrix stores 10 left singular vectors (500 each), 10 right singular vectors (500 each), and 10 singular values: 10*500 + 10*500 + 10 = 10,010 values, approximately 10,000.": "",
  "A neuroscientist records brain activity from 128 electrodes over time and applies PCA. She finds that the first two principal components separate patients into two clusters. What type of analysis has PCA facilitated?": "",
  "Time series forecasting": "",
  "Regression analysis": "",
  "Hypothesis testing": "",
  "Exploratory data visualization and clustering": "",
  "By reducing 128 dimensions to 2, PCA enables visualization of the data in a 2D scatter plot where clusters become visible. This is exploratory analysis -- PCA reveals structure without prior assumptions.": "",
  "A recommendation system has a 10,000 users x 5,000 items ratings matrix with 95% missing entries. A data scientist wants to apply PCA. What practical issue does she face?": "",
  "Standard PCA requires a complete data matrix; the missing values must be handled first": "",
  "PCA cannot process matrices larger than 1000x1000": "",
  "PCA only works on square matrices": "",
  "The matrix has too few features": "",
  "Standard PCA requires complete data to compute the covariance matrix. With 95% missing entries, she needs techniques like imputation, probabilistic PCA, or matrix completion before applying PCA.": "",
  "A climate scientist applies PCA to global temperature measurements from 500 weather stations over 30 years. The first principal component often represents what physical phenomenon?": "",
  "Instrument calibration errors": "",
  "Random measurement noise": "",
  "The global mean temperature trend (overall warming/cooling pattern)": "",
  "Daily temperature fluctuations": "",
  "The first principal component of global temperature data typically captures the dominant large-scale pattern, which is the overall global temperature trend. Subsequent components capture regional patterns and oscillations like El Nino.": "",
  "A text mining researcher represents 10,000 documents using a vocabulary of 50,000 words (TF-IDF vectors). She applies PCA to reduce to 100 dimensions. What is the approximate compression ratio?": "",
  "500:1": "",
  "100:1": "",
  "10:1": "",
  "50:1": "",
  "Each document goes from 50,000 dimensions to 100 dimensions, a compression ratio of 50,000:100 = 500:1. The 100 PCA dimensions capture the most important semantic patterns in the vocabulary.": "",
  "A manufacturing engineer monitors 20 process variables and applies PCA for anomaly detection. She constructs a T^2 statistic using the first 3 principal components. A new observation has T^2 = 15 when the 99% control limit is 11.3. What should she conclude?": "",
  "More principal components are needed": "",
  "The PCA model is incorrect": "",
  "The process is operating normally": "",
  "The observation is an anomaly because T^2 exceeds the control limit": "",
  "Since T^2 = 15 > 11.3 (the 99% control limit), the observation is statistically unusual at the 1% significance level. This signals a potential anomaly or process fault that warrants investigation.": ""
}